I'd love to use `fastcache` in my library, but for that I can't set `maxsize` parameter of fastcache myself, but need to assign it at runtime. 

I have tried to write my decorator, but with mixed success: the decorator works (albeit ugly, many nested levels) but it breaks the `cache_info()` statistics which is needed for testing. 

Let's give an example of my usecase:

```
class A:
  @cached
  def foo_long(arg1, ..)
```

How to get the arguments to fastcache?:
- "cached" method will have an argument `cachesize` which would be read by the decorator: 

```
@cached
def foo_long(arg1, cachesize=1000):
```
- or fastcache takes optional argument `readFrom`: string, that will define a name of instance member variable holding the value for fastcache: 

```
@cached(readFrom='_cacheSize')
def foo_long(arg1):
```

Bonus points which I couldn't achieve:
- make `cache_info()` work with these decorators
- adapt clru_cache to use this code, so I don't have to use the lru_cache python wrapper.

What do you think about these suggestions? Thanks

I would flip these two lines:

```
  clist *oldfirst = root->next;
  clist *first = PyObject_New(clist, &clist_type);
```

at https://github.com/pbrady/fastcache/blob/master/src/_lrucache.c#L258
